## crates/ctx-scan/src/hash.rs

Computes and diffs the content-hash tree that drives change detection for
the whole summarization pipeline — the CACT (content-addressed context
tree) mechanism. Freshness is decided purely from SHA-256 hashes stored
in `.context/<dir>/hashes.json`, never from git state, so gitignored or
uncommitted edits are still detected and a clean git tree isn't mistaken
for a fresh summary tree.

Core model: `TreeState.dirs` maps repo-relative directory (`""` = root)
to a `DirNode` (from `ctx_core::hashtree`) whose `children` map holds
either `f:<hex>` (file hash) or `d:<hex>` (child directory's aggregate
hash) entries. `aggregate()` computes each directory's hash deepest-first
by hashing its sorted `name=hash\n` child lines, then folds the result
into the parent as a `d:` entry — this is what makes any leaf change
propagate to the root.

Key functions: `compute(base, files) -> Result<TreeState, ScanError>`
rebuilds the tree from current file contents. `load_stored<F: Fs>(fs,
current) -> TreeState` reads sidecars per directory in `current`; a
missing or corrupt sidecar is treated as absent (not an error), meaning
that directory reads as stale. `store<F: Fs>(fs, state) ->
Result<(), ScanError>` persists all nodes. `diff(current, stored) ->
Staleness` yields `stale_dirs` (deepest-first order, for bottom-up
regeneration), `changed_files`, and `orphan_leaves` (source deleted but
`.ctx` still recorded). `record_missing_artifacts<F: Fs>(fs, current,
out: &mut Staleness)` separately checks that every expected
`rollup.ctx`/leaf `.ctx` actually exists on disk — this catches summaries
deleted by hand or never generated, since hash-only diffing can't see
artifact absence (a gap here is invisible to plain `diff`).

Depends on `ctx_summarize::cpath` for the `.context/` mirroring
convention and `ctx_summarize::fs::Fs` trait for testable I/O — both
must stay in sync with how the rest of the summarizer lays out context
directories.